Show HN: Quick userscript to hide Hacker News posts based on domain
text:
I made this after seeing this HN post[0] asking if this was possible.

There are some extensions that can do this, but they also redo lots of the HN UI, which I think is unnecessary.

It just took a few minutes to make; I'm mainly posting this so if someone searches for it they could find it.

Use Tampermonkey or Greasemonkey to install, edit it slightly to add in your domains.

title: Ask HN: How will Google differentiate between content written by AI and human?
text:
The chatGPT broke the internet these last days by invading the web with screenshots of the different exchanges between testers and artificial intelligence. We can ask it what we want, like writing an article or a publication (don't worry, I'm the one typing behind my keyboard).

I was wondering last night how Google (not to mention the other engines) will adapt its SEO strategies to discern a human's written content from an AI's content.

Because if everyone starts to generate articles with AIs, the web will become a pile of content created by AIs based on content written by humans for humans. But we know that training models are based on text corpora from different sources (including the web).

Where is the border? The more content generated by AIs, the more the new AIs will train on content generated by other AIs to create new content.

We will end up reading content that humans no longer wrote, which could become almost rare.

Content is one of many variables taken into account by the algorithm to index pages, but it will be interesting to see how search engines will solve this issue.

Tell me what you think:

title: Ask HN: AI supported size estimation of user stories
text:
I was just wondering:

Can we use ChatGPT (or similar technology) to come up with user story estimations?

I see the problem that for many large projects, it is very hard to give accurate estimates, thus delivering features late.

Estimation is very hard and complex, but maybe can AI have the capability to see through the complexity and give us better estimates?

Ask HN: How) Do You Measure Product Market Fit?
text:
Superhuman famously measures PMF with this question:

How disappointed would you be if you couldn't use Superhuman anymore?

> Very disappointed > Somewhat disappointed > Not disappointed

If 40% or more would be Very disappointed you're on the right track!

(Rahul adds more to the method, its pretty cool actually, link below)

My question is:

How do you go about finding PMF? How do you measure your progress?

Thanks!
